00:02:14.570 --> 00:02:19.420
And as probably your docents,
your tour guides have told you,

00:02:19.420 --> 00:02:21.740
this beautiful building
that we're in today,

00:02:21.740 --> 00:02:24.140
the Jefferson Building
is really a testimony

00:02:24.140 --> 00:02:26.810
to a particular moment in time.

00:02:26.810 --> 00:02:28.110
The particular moment in time

00:02:28.110 --> 00:02:32.180
when the United States was
becoming a world power at the turn

00:02:32.180 --> 00:02:36.050
of the century from the 19th
century into the 20th century.

00:02:36.050 --> 00:02:40.380
So the building stands
really for the idea

00:02:40.380 --> 00:02:43.980
that the United States would
become a world leader as far

00:02:43.980 --> 00:02:48.650
as knowledge is concerned and
as far as learning is concerned

00:02:48.650 --> 00:02:51.950
and also educational
access for everyone.

00:02:51.950 --> 00:02:55.550
The library has adopted the
ideals of Thomas Jefferson.

00:02:55.550 --> 00:02:59.440
We know Thomas Jefferson was the
founder in some ways of the Library

00:02:59.440 --> 00:03:04.930
of Congress because he provided us
with the very first books to serve

00:03:04.930 --> 00:03:07.010
as the Library of Congress.

00:03:07.010 --> 00:03:10.900
He believed that free, unhampered
pursuit of truth by an informed

00:03:10.900 --> 00:03:14.690
and involved citizen --
citizenry was necessary --

00:03:14.690 --> 00:03:17.200
was necessary criteria
for democracy.

00:03:17.200 --> 00:03:20.770
It didn't mean that that was a
nice thing to have a democracy,

00:03:20.770 --> 00:03:24.450
but it was something that
had to exist for democracy

00:03:24.450 --> 00:03:26.990
to function and to flourish.

00:03:26.990 --> 00:03:31.900
And there was a time when most
libraries strictly guarded their

00:03:31.900 --> 00:03:37.420
doors to knowledge, so libraries
weren't always necessarily open

00:03:37.420 --> 00:03:39.410
or free to everyone.

00:03:39.410 --> 00:03:43.190
But this institution was
always dedicated to the idea

00:03:43.190 --> 00:03:45.750
of universal access
and equal opportunity

00:03:45.750 --> 00:03:48.610
and we still are obviously
to this day.

00:03:48.610 --> 00:03:51.380
Everyone is welcome to
the Library of Congress.

00:03:51.380 --> 00:03:52.830
And I feel very comfortable saying

00:03:52.830 --> 00:03:58.360
that because our new librarian
really espouses that --

00:03:58.360 --> 00:04:01.990
that principle and talks
about it on a daily basis.

00:04:01.990 --> 00:04:06.830
And what she means by that is the
youngest people, and she calls them

00:04:06.830 --> 00:04:11.690
"scholars in training," people that
are not even, can't even read yet,

00:04:11.690 --> 00:04:15.160
kids that can't even read yet,
welcome to the Library of Congress.

00:04:15.160 --> 00:04:18.590
We have a Young Readers
center just one floor down,

00:04:18.590 --> 00:04:21.940
and she enjoys going there,
reading stories to them,

00:04:21.940 --> 00:04:25.560
reading books to them, trying to
get kids engaged in the notion

00:04:25.560 --> 00:04:30.890
of reading and of learning, all the
way up to our high school students

00:04:30.890 --> 00:04:35.360 position:56%
who we encourage to use the Library
of Congress; to our college students

00:04:35.360 --> 00:04:39.650
and then our most senior scholars
who come here to the library

00:04:39.650 --> 00:04:43.490
to write books and
important research articles.

00:04:43.490 --> 00:04:47.880
So the library really belongs
to everyone from the whole range

00:04:47.880 --> 00:04:54.080 position:56%
of early learners all the way to our
-- our most senior intellectuals,

00:04:54.080 --> 00:04:57.400 position:56%
and she really means that sincerely.

00:04:57.400 --> 00:05:01.630
The Library of Congress is --
I'm not sure if you know this,

00:05:01.630 --> 00:05:06.710
but it is the largest
repository of human knowledge

00:05:06.710 --> 00:05:08.500
in the world, which is pretty cool.

00:05:08.500 --> 00:05:09.800
I mean it is.

00:05:09.800 --> 00:05:14.690
It is the place that has the
most amount in one location

00:05:14.690 --> 00:05:19.470
of information and
knowledge in the entire world.

00:05:19.470 --> 00:05:21.120
And that's pretty special.

00:05:21.120 --> 00:05:22.430
We have 3,000 people.

00:05:22.430 --> 00:05:23.810
I'll tell you a little
bit about the numbers.

00:05:23.810 --> 00:05:26.060
So what does that mean?

00:05:26.060 --> 00:05:28.450
3,000 people work here at the --

00:05:28.450 --> 00:05:32.170
about 3,000 people work here
at the Library of Congress

00:05:32.170 --> 00:05:36.670
where the main research arm
of the United States Congress,

00:05:36.670 --> 00:05:39.440
so we take that mission
very, very seriously.

00:05:39.440 --> 00:05:42.310
Before I came to work in outreach
here at the Library of Congress,

00:05:42.310 --> 00:05:45.550
I worked at the Congressional
Research Service for many years,

00:05:45.550 --> 00:05:48.430
which is a division of the
Library of Congress that works

00:05:48.430 --> 00:05:52.030
to serve members of congress
and staff, providing them

00:05:52.030 --> 00:05:57.270
with nonpartisan information and
analysis about public policy issues

00:05:57.270 --> 00:06:00.290
that are being debated today.

00:06:00.290 --> 00:06:05.520
We're also surrounded by 36 million
catalogue books here at the Library

00:06:05.520 --> 00:06:10.720
of Congress, print materials
and 460 foreign languages,

00:06:10.720 --> 00:06:16.020
69 million manuscripts, the
largest rare book collection in all

00:06:16.020 --> 00:06:19.060
of North American and the
world's largest collection

00:06:19.060 --> 00:06:23.270
of legal materials,
films, maps, comic books,

00:06:23.270 --> 00:06:26.320
sheet music and sound recordings.

00:06:26.320 --> 00:06:30.480
So, it's not -- The Library
of Congress is not just books.

00:06:30.480 --> 00:06:33.180
Yes, books are a very,
very important part

00:06:33.180 --> 00:06:36.720
of our 160 million
object collections,

00:06:36.720 --> 00:06:39.750
so that's the foundation
of our collection.

00:06:39.750 --> 00:06:42.980
But the library also -- Library
of Congress also recognizes

00:06:42.980 --> 00:06:45.040
that you can learn from
a lot of different types

00:06:45.040 --> 00:06:47.550
of materials and not just books.

00:06:47.550 --> 00:06:50.140
So the library collects
widely, hence the notion

00:06:50.140 --> 00:06:52.230
that the library is
the largest repository

00:06:52.230 --> 00:06:54.800
of human knowledge in the world.

00:06:54.800 --> 00:06:57.220
So the amount of information
is when you think

00:06:57.220 --> 00:07:02.940
about it is pretty mind
boggling, 160 million objects,

00:07:02.940 --> 00:07:07.780 position:56%
160 million items that you can learn
from at the Library of Congress.

00:07:07.780 --> 00:07:11.470
But then you might say, well,
"Why is that so important today?"

00:07:11.470 --> 00:07:13.230
You know, why is it so important

00:07:13.230 --> 00:07:16.710
to have physical collections
of -- of these items?

00:07:16.710 --> 00:07:19.090
Because, you know,
this phone, right,

00:07:19.090 --> 00:07:24.220
in my pocket can put easily 160
million pieces of information

00:07:24.220 --> 00:07:27.600
at my fingertips, and I can
walk around with it, you know,

00:07:27.600 --> 00:07:29.160
all day here at the library.

00:07:29.160 --> 00:07:30.640
It can walk around with it at home.

00:07:30.640 --> 00:07:35.920
You can use it for all kinds
of purposes, just curiosity

00:07:35.920 --> 00:07:38.900
or actual learning,
scholarship research.

00:07:38.900 --> 00:07:41.370
It can be used today.

00:07:41.370 --> 00:07:44.640
You can google any question that
you don't know the answer to.

00:07:44.640 --> 00:07:46.700
If you're at my house,
you ask Alexa.

00:07:46.700 --> 00:07:49.270
That's what I like to
do because I'm lazy.

00:07:49.270 --> 00:07:53.860
So now I talk to, you know,
almost like a virtual robot

00:07:53.860 --> 00:07:56.060
to answer questions for me.

00:07:56.060 --> 00:07:58.160
But the question is,
so you have access.

00:07:58.160 --> 00:08:00.190
All this information
is at your fingertips.

00:08:00.190 --> 00:08:03.040
There's not a question of the
fact that we don't have access

00:08:03.040 --> 00:08:07.030
to information today, and you
don't have to necessarily come

00:08:07.030 --> 00:08:10.570
to a library to -- to read a book
or to read a magazine article

00:08:10.570 --> 00:08:12.580
or to read a newspaper article.

00:08:12.580 --> 00:08:14.410
But the question is,
can you distinguish

00:08:14.410 --> 00:08:17.220
between reliable sources?

00:08:17.220 --> 00:08:21.530
How do you know what is
actually factually correct?

00:08:21.530 --> 00:08:24.340
Do you know the right
questions to ask

00:08:24.340 --> 00:08:26.500
to get the answers that you need?

00:08:26.500 --> 00:08:27.860
And that works for anything.

00:08:27.860 --> 00:08:29.720
That works if you're
using your phone.

00:08:29.720 --> 00:08:32.050
That works if you're using
something like Alexa.

00:08:32.050 --> 00:08:34.720
My husband is very bad at
asking Alexa questions.

00:08:34.720 --> 00:08:39.260
He asks her questions in the wrong
way and he never gets good answers.

00:08:39.260 --> 00:08:42.190
So, I mean, just using a
simple device like that,

00:08:42.190 --> 00:08:45.550
if you don't know how to use
it, then there may be a lot

00:08:45.550 --> 00:08:49.510
of information inside that
device, but you can't gain access

00:08:49.510 --> 00:08:51.930
to the information that you need.

00:08:51.930 --> 00:08:54.960
And that's really where
libraries play a major role.

00:08:54.960 --> 00:08:57.150
The vast amount of information

00:08:57.150 --> 00:09:00.800
that has now been made
available has made libraries

00:09:00.800 --> 00:09:02.690
and librarians even more important.

00:09:02.690 --> 00:09:05.270
Some people would argue it's
made libraries less important

00:09:05.270 --> 00:09:08.420
because we're all walking
around with virtual libraries

00:09:08.420 --> 00:09:10.910
in our pockets or in our backpacks.

00:09:10.910 --> 00:09:12.450
But that's not really true.

00:09:12.450 --> 00:09:15.300
Simply, access to more
information doesn't mean

00:09:15.300 --> 00:09:19.310
that we don't need experts like
we provide here at the Library

00:09:19.310 --> 00:09:22.260
of Congress or any library,
right, the public libraries,

00:09:22.260 --> 00:09:25.050
research libraries that
we don't require experts

00:09:25.050 --> 00:09:29.400
to help us find the right
answers and the right sources.

00:09:29.400 --> 00:09:31.300
As Dr. Hayden likes to say,

00:09:31.300 --> 00:09:34.990
"Librarians are the
original search engines."

00:09:34.990 --> 00:09:37.490
Library staff makes
it easier for you

00:09:37.490 --> 00:09:41.600
to access the correct
information so that you know

00:09:41.600 --> 00:09:45.600
